[1
Date: Wed 11 Apr 2001 05:04:59
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Asia Daily News, AFP, Wed 11 Apr 12:32 AM SGT 2001 [edited
spected.html>

Second Case of Suspected Hemorrhagic Fever in Nyeri
---------------------------------------------------
NAIROBI: Kenya's Ministry of Health has put in place emergency measures
following the hospitalization of a second patient suspected to be suffering
from a hemorrhagic fever. A statement released here on Tue 10 Apr 2001 by
Health Minister Sam Ongeri said that a 19-year-old male recruit from
Kiganjo Police Training College had been admitted to the Mathari Mission
Hospital in the central town of Nyeri on Sun 8 Apr 2001 and was examined
the following day by a surveillance team. The patient had complained of
malaise and headache for a week before he developed diarrhoea on Mon 9 Apr
2001, the statement said, adding that he was stable and in isolation.
A 24-year-old woman with symptoms of haemorrhagic fever, also a recruit at
the Police College, died at the Consolata Mission Hospital near Nyeri on
Mon 2 Apr 2001, a day after she was admitted. Ongeri said that although
Ebola virus had been practically ruled out [as the cause of her illness,
his Ministry has not dismissed the possibility of hemorrhagic fever and has
set up isolation rooms both at Kiganjo and Mathari Mission Hospital. The
Ministry has also put in place and distributed hemorrhagic fever management
guidelines. A surveillance team consisting of experts from the Health
Ministry, the Kenya Medical Research Institute (KEMRI), and the World
Health Organisation (WHO) [had been constituted.
